{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a7aaaeb-b215-4f47-a347-77823513c663","content":"Here's a step-by-step diagnostic and fix plan:\n\n---\n\n### Phase 1 — Diagnose\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Confirm which SDK(s) are installed\ndotnet --list-sdks\n\n# 2. See what workloads are currently installed (and if any are stale)\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 3. Check for a global.json pinning an older SDK in your repo\nGet-Content .\\global.json   # if it exists\n```\n\nLook for: version mismatches between the SDK you just installed and the workloads that were installed for the *previous* SDK.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2 — Fix workloads\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates every installed workload to match your current SDK band. Run it from an **elevated** (admin) terminal:\n\n```powershell\n# 4. Update all workloads to match the new SDK\ndotnet workload update\n\n# 5. If the MAUI workload is missing entirely, install it\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\nIf your project targets a specific SDK version via `global.json`, either **update that file** to the new SDK version or remove it so the latest SDK is used.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3 — Fix Android SDK\n\n```powershell\n# 6. Confirm the Android SDK path is set and valid\n#    MAUI stores it in: %LOCALAPPDATA%\\Android\\Sdk  (or via env var)\necho $env:ANDROID_HOME\necho $env:ANDROID_SDK_ROOT\n\n# 7. Accept all pending Android SDK licenses\n& \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --licenses\n\n# 8. Let the MAUI workload install/update required Android components\ndotnet build -t:InstallAndroidDependencies -f net9.0-android `\n  -p:AndroidSdkDirectory=\"$env:ANDROID_HOME\" `\n  -p:AcceptAndroidSDKLicenses=true\n```\n\n*(Replace `net9.0-android` with your actual TFM, e.g. `net8.0-android`.)*\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4 — Verify\n\n```powershell\n# 9. Confirm workloads are consistent\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 10. Build the project\ndotnet build\n```\n\n---\n\n### Key notes\n\n| Concern | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Is `workload update` safe? | Yes — it only updates workload manifests/packs to the matching SDK band. |\n| Should I uninstall old SDKs? | Not required, but you can clean orphaned packs with `dotnet workload clean`. |\n| `global.json` conflict? | If it pins an older SDK, either update it or delete it. |\n\nRun these steps in order and the build should succeed. Let me know if you hit a specific error along the way.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ff2c7224-4edb-42fb-94d0-7e47cde25399","outputTokens":694},"id":"369ef48b-d2a4-4edc-911c-0f95429d0e85","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:56:10.725Z","parentId":"de2718ac-4d1b-4f1f-802e-37f9b924b397"}
